# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ambury-regional-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area of the park has seen human interaction for approximately 700 years, with evidence of habitation dating back to early Māori iwi such as Waitaha and Rapuwai during the early periods of Māori habitation in New Zealand.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Following the arrival of Pākehā in the 19th century, the area saw widespread deforestation, farming, and quarrying, significantly modifying the area's environment.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this, the park is one of the most modified landscapes of any of New Zealand's national parks, with management of the park largely focusing on regeneration and restoration of the traditional ecosystem.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was first established in 1942 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's 1642 visit in New Zealand, when he became the first European to sight the islands.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It has since been progressively expanded from its original borders, the most recent of which involved the addition of 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet after a successful crowdfunding campaign.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The coastal area was inhabited for hundreds of years by Māori prior to the arrival of Europeans, with sites throughout the area occupied both seasonally and permanently.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In addition to harvesting food from the local forests, estuaries and waters, locals grew kūmara.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Historical records indicate a pā was established at Auckland Point by Pohea, who travelled there around 1450 from the Whanganui area.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] From the mid-1500s Muaūpoko (formerly known as Ngāi Tara) occupied the area until the early 1600s, when they were ousted by Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri were present when Abel Tasman reached Golden Bay / Mohua in 1642.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was founded in 1942, largely through the efforts of ornithologist and author Pérrine Moncrieff to have land reserved for the purpose.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Moncrieff served on the park board from 1943 to 1974.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was opened on 18 December 1942 to mark the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's visit.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Those in attendance at the opening ceremony at Tarakohe included Charles van der Plas, as personal representative of the Netherlands' Queen, Wilhelmina.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The idea for the park had been under consideration since June 1938.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Crown set aside 15,225 hectares (37,622 acres), comprising 8,900 hectares (21,900 acres) of proposed state forest, 5,809 hectares (14,354 acres) of Crown land and 554 hectares (1,368 acres) of other reserve land for the national park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Golden Bay Cement Company donated the land where the Abel Tasman Monument and a memorial plaque was sited.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area's primary historic interest was the visit of Tasman in 1642, D'Urville in 1827, and the New Zealand Company barques *Whitby* and *Will Watch*, and brig *Arrow* in 1841.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The site was also of significant botanical interest.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] By 1946 the park had reached 15,534 hectares (38,386 acres) in area with additional land purchases.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] A further 844 hectares (2,085 acres) at Tōtaranui, formerly owned by William Gibbs, was acquired from J S Campbell in 1949 and added to the park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] About 6,100 hectares (15,000 acres) have been added since.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2008 an extra 7.9 km2 (790 ha; 3.1 sq mi), including the formerly private land known as Hadfields Clearing, were added to the park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2016, a further 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet was purchased by New Zealanders in a crowdfunding campaign.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Covering an area of 237 km2 (92 sq mi; 59,000 acres), the park is the smallest of New Zealand's national parks.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It consists of forested, hilly country to the north of the valleys of the Tākaka and Riwaka Rivers, and is bounded to the north by the waters of Golden Bay / Mohua and Tasman Bay.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains some of the islands off the coast including the Tata Islands in Golden Bay / Mohua, and Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island, and Fisherman Island in Tasman Bay.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park does not extend beyond Mean High Water Mark on the adjacent coast.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Between Mean High Water and Mean Low Water Springs, the beaches are gazetted as a Scenic Reserve, covering 7.74 km2 (2.99 sq mi) in total.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Tonga Island Marine Reserve adjoins part of the park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Monument, though not located in the park, commemorates the first contact between Europeans and Māori and is located near the northern end of the park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Abel Tasman National Park stands out from most other National parks of New Zealand, given that a large area of it has undergone extensive environmental modification in its history.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Early European settlers burned or cleared much of the forest, only to find that the soil was unsuitable for farming.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This practise not only destroyed much of the shrubland and forests, but also introduced invasive plants found throughout the modern-day park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] However, as time progresses, the original ecosystems and forests are slowly returning.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains varied habitats, including coastal forests, sub-alpine bogs, and sand dunes.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this diversity, many different species can be found.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The islands of the park, in particular Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island and Fisherman Island which are the largest, have been disturbed less and have no introduced mammalian predators.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result the islands have species not found elsewhere in the park and there are more restrictions to visitor access.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Though much of the parkland is pasture or covered with shrubs, valley areas contain forests of rātā, mataī, miro and hinau.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Over 70 species of birds have been recorded in the park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Some of the birds that can frequently be seen are petrels, shags, penguins, gulls, terns, and herons.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Possums, wild pigs, deer, and goats can also be seen in the park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Coast Track is a popular tramping track that follows the coastline and is one of the Department of Conservation's Great Walks; the Abel Tasman Inland Track is less frequented.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Other walks in the park, such as the Wainui Falls Track are considered "short walks".
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Kayaking, camping and sightseeing are other activities.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Access to the park is usually via the small settlement of Mārahau or Kaiteriteri (by water taxi).
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The nearest large town is Motueka, 20 kilometres (12 mi) to the south.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Dogs (excepting guide dogs) are not allowed in the park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation administers the National Park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Scenic Reserve is administered by the Tasman District Council Chief Executive and Department of Conservation's Nelson / Marlborough Conservator.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Activities in adjoining coastal waters are Tasman District Council's responsibility.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] These areas operate under separate regulations.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Interior, consisting of the park areas further inland.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Park plans include ecological surveys, pest control, and protection of heritage areas and caves.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Islands, encompassing all islands within the park, some of which are closed to the public. key priorities include keeping them free of invasive pests, reintroducing native species, and minimizing human impacts.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2012 Project Janszoon, a privately funded trust, was set up to restore the park's ecosystems.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The trust takes its name from Tasman's middle name *Janszoon*.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It is aiming to complete the restoration in time for the 400th anniversary of Tasman's visit and the park's 100th anniversary in 2042.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation and Project Janszoon developed a free virtual visitor centre for downloading to smartphones or tablets.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The application provides information about the Park's history, its flora and fauna, points of interest, weather, walking tracks, and tides.
[src:ambury-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This virtual visitor centre is free of charge and can be found through the App Store or Google Play Store.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The mountains, forests, tussock lands and river valleys are used for tramping, fishing kayaking, horse riding and hunting.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Both the park and neighbouring Ben Avon Station are located near the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve, a dark-sky preserve, and are used for astronomy.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The town is serviced by the tourist town of Omarama.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The park was established in 2005, and includes the Birchwood Station leasehold farm the New Zealand Government bought back for NZ$10 million in 2004.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] It contained extensive wetlands that had remained largely undeveloped.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Birchwood Station continued normal farming operations until the end of the leasehold in 2010.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The road to the former Birchwood Station homestead stopped being regularly maintained by Waitaki District Council in 2011.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] In 2014, ecologist Peter Espie reported a decrease in native plant species in the park, and suggested introducing grazing management.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Parts of the 2020 Disney film *Mulan* were filmed in the Ahuriri Valley near the conservation park, including the training camp scenes and some battle scenes.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The airport is one of New Zealand's most important infrastructure assets, providing several thousand jobs for the region.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] It handled 71 per cent of the country's international air passenger arrivals and departures in 2000.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] It is one of only two commercial airports in New Zealand that can handle Airbus A380 jet aircraft (the other being Christchurch).
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The airport has a single 3,635 m (11,926 ft) runway, 05R/23L, which is Cat IIIb capable (at a reduced rate of movements) in the 23L direction.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] It has a capacity of about 45 flight movements per hour, and is currently the busiest single-runway airport in Oceania.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In November 2007 work began on a new northern runway, to be built in several stages and to be used mainly by smaller aircraft, freeing up capacity on the main runway.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The project has been repeatedly delayed and is now expected to be completed in 2038, a delay of more than a decade.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The airport covers 1,500 hectares (5.8 sq. miles).
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] At present, the airport has an international and a domestic terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In 2023, AIAL announced plans for all jet services to operate from a single expanded terminal, with turboprop services continuing to use the existing domestic facility.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The site of the airport was first used as an airfield by the Auckland Aero Club.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In 1928, the club leased some land from a dairy farmer to accommodate the club's three De Havilland Gypsy Moths.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The club president noted at the time that the site "has many advantages of vital importance for an aerodrome and training ground.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] It has good approaches, is well drained and is free from power lines, buildings and fogs." Prior to rebuilding, this was known as Mangere Aerodrome.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] From 1948, the RNZAF Base Auckland at Whenuapai served as the civilian airport for Auckland.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] This was chosen, despite the hills adjacent to Whenuapai limiting the ability of newer aircraft to use the facilities, to the lack of cost to the Auckland City Council, as the site was already established as an RNZAF base.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] A September 1948 report by Sir Frederick Tymms recommended that Whenuapai Airport be replaced with a larger purpose-built airport located in either Māngere or Pakuranga.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In 1958, the New Zealand Government commissioned Leigh Fisher Associates to survey and design the international airport at Māngere.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In 1960 work started to transform the site into Auckland's main airport.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Much of the runway is on land reclaimed from the Manukau Harbour.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The first flight to leave was an Air New Zealand DC-8 in November 1965, bound for Sydney.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The airport was officially opened the following year, with a 'grand air pageant' on Auckland Anniversary weekend, 29 to 31 January 1966.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Upon the airport's opening, the runway was 2,591 metres (8,500 ft) long.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The runway was extended westward to 3,292 metres (10,800 ft) in 1973.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Qantas commenced the first scheduled Boeing 747 service out of Auckland on Friday 8 December 1972.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] A new international terminal was built in 1977.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Prior to this, all flights used what is now the domestic terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] After the news of famous aviatrix Jean Batten's death reached New Zealand in 1987, the International Terminal was named the Jean Batten Terminal in her honour.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In 2005, the international terminal was altered, separating arriving and departing passengers.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Previously taxiway 'Alpha' (parallel to the main runway) had been modified and designated as Runway 23R/05L so that rehabilitation work could be completed on the main runway 23L/05R.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] After the work was completed, the temporary runway reverted to taxiway alpha, although the main runway retained its L/R designations.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In 2007, construction began on a second runway to the north of the current one.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Initially the new runway would have been 1,200-metre (3,900 ft) long and catered for regional flights operated by Air New Zealand using turboprop aircraft.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] This would have cost $32 million and would have improved the efficiency of the airport by removing smaller planes (which require longer separation distances from the air turbulence wakes of preceding jet airliners) from the main runway.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] At a later stage, the runway would have been lengthened to 1,950 metres (6,400 ft) to allow it be used by small jets (such as the Boeing 737 and Airbus A320) on domestic and trans-Tasman flights.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In August 2009, however, the project was put on hold due to a downturn in air travel, and later in 2010 the project was suspended.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In 2009, an extension to the international terminal was constructed, creating Pier B.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Pier B covers 5,500 square metres (59,000 sq ft) and has been designed to allow for the addition of new gates when required.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] It currently has two gates, both capable of handling Airbus A380 aircraft.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In May 2009, Emirates became the first airline to fly the A380 to Auckland, using the aircraft on its daily Dubai–Sydney–Auckland route.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In 2013, the domestic terminal undertook a series of upgrades costing a total of $30 million.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Stage one ran from January 2013 to March 2013, and involved changes to the drop off points and roads outside the terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In the second half of 2013, the baggage claim belts were lengthened, parts of the apron was changed, and new corridors were connected to the jetbridges.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The two different sides to the terminals now share a centralised security screening area following the upgrade and an extra storey was added to the western wing to provide an airside connection between the Air New Zealand side of the terminal and the Jetstar side of the terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The 2015 Annual Report stated that Pier B would be extended.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The extension was completed in 2018, with two new gates (17 and 18) being built.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] These gates can accommodate two wide-body aircraft or four narrowbody aircraft.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Auckland Airport recorded its first loss since listing, posting an underlying deficit of NZ$41.8 million for the 2021 financial year after revenue fell 50 per cent as traffic collapsed.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] On 27 January 2023, record-breaking rainfall flooded both terminals, forcing Auckland Airport to close for almost 24 hours and leaving hundreds of travellers stranded as all flights were cancelled or diverted.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In March 2023 the airport announced plans to replace the existing domestic terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The project is estimated to cost $3.9 billion.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The plan is controversial, with airlines expressing concerns at the cost and the resulting increases in landing charges.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] 15 September 2024, the airport announced it would raise NZ$1.4 billion in equity to fund a NZ$6.6 billion programme to upgrade the runway and airfield and improve connections between domestic and international flights.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The programme is opposed by Air New Zealand and Qantas, who argue that higher airport charges will render travel unaffordable.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Auckland Airport consists of two terminals; the International Terminal and the Domestic Terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The two terminals are located approximately 500 m (1,600 ft) apart and are connected by a free shuttle bus service and a signposted walkway.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The airport has 65 gates in total, 23 with jetbridges and 42 remote stands for aircraft parking.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The international terminal building has three levels, with departures occupying the eastern half of the terminal and arrivals occupying the western half.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Departing passengers check-in on the ground floor, then proceed to the first floor though landside retail, immigration and security, and duty-free, before proceeding to the departure gates on the second floor.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Arriving passengers arrive on the first floor, passing through duty-free and immigration, before proceeding to the ground floor through baggage claim, customs and biosecurity, and into the arrivals hall.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The terminal has 22 gates total - 10 airbridge gates (1 through 10) and four bus gates (4A through 4D) in Pier A, and four airbridge gates (15 through 18) and four bus gates (16A through 16D) in Pier B.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] There is another gate number 19 is next to 18 without an airbridge.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Each international pier feature a tomokanga (Māori carved gateway) in the arrivals area accompanied by a karanga audio recording, symbolising Auckland Airport as a major international gateway and welcoming passengers to New Zealand.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The Pier A tomokanga was installed in 1994, while the Pier B tomokanga was installed when the pier opened in 2009.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] On 2 October 2012 Emirates began operating the Dubai–Melbourne–Auckland with an A380, having previously operated the route with a B777-300ER.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In 2014, Singapore Airlines was the second airline to operate A380s at the airport.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The two previously separate domestic terminal buildings have now been connected by a common retail area.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The Jetstar check-in area is located in the western end of the terminal, in the building previously used by Ansett New Zealand, Qantas, and Pacific Blue.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The Air New Zealand check-in area is located in the centre of the terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] There are nine gates that have jetbridges in the domestic terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Jetstar domestic A320 services operate from gates 20–23 (jetbridge gates).
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Gate 24 (tarmac gate) is used by both Jetstar and Air New Zealand's A320 aircraft.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Gates 60–63 were used for Jetstar regional flights, with 62 and 63 being bus gates in a separate building at the Jetstar end of the terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Gates 20 and 21 were turned into 60 and 61 during peak regional times.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Air New Zealand mainline services operate from gates 24–33.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Gates 28 through to 33 all have jetbridges, while gates 25, 26 and 27 don't exist.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Air New Zealand turboprop services operate from the regional section of the domestic terminal, along with Barrier Air and Air Chathams.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] This is located at the eastern end of the terminal and consists of gates 34–50 (excluding gate numbers 37, 38 and 44, which do not exist).
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] These gates are linked to the terminal by covered walkways, and passengers walk across the apron to the aircraft.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Barrier Air also uses remote gates 51–59, whilst further to the east, gates 101–106 are used for business jets and long-term parking.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In 1993, the CAA instituted the requirement that all international airports in New Zealand must keep airside departing and arriving passengers separate.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Auckland Airport was granted an exemption to this rule, allowing the airside mingling of arriving and departing passengers to continue, on the basis that all international flights operating into Auckland originated from airports with adequate security screening.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Following the September 11, 2001 attacks and further regulation by the ICAO, the CAA required the airport to physically separate arriving and departing passengers by 2006.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In the interim period until passenger separation was achieved, flights to the United States as well as all Qantas, and for a short time Cathay Pacific, flights were restricted to departing from gates where a secondary X-ray and metal detector inspection was operating.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] To physically separate arriving and departing passengers, Auckland Airport decided to build a new departure level on top of the existing one, with the existing floor becoming the arrivals level.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The existing departure lounges were kept by installing glass walls to separate the waiting areas from the newly designed arrivals corridor, and escalators were installed to transport passengers from the new departures level down to each departure lounge.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The modifications to the terminal were completed in December 2005, and also involved the expansion of retail space within the pier by 600 square metres (6,500 sq ft) and an increase in the number of bus gates to four.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Auckland Airport owned radio frequencies over a 15-year period.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] It purchased the Radio Hauraki frequency 1476 AM in 1990, and began operating adult contemporary and flight information radio station Info Music from the domestic terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] It purchased 1XD Counties Manukau L Double L and its 1404 AM, 1548 AM and 702 AM frequencies in 1992, and changed the station name to Info Music Counties 1476 and then Airport Radio AKL1476.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The 1476 frequency was leased to Independent Broadcasting Company in 1993, which used it at various times for Auckland 1476, The Breeze on 91, Lifestyle Radio, and Today 99.8FM.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] It was leased to talkback station The Point 1XD in 1994, and made available to Auckland Radio Trust to rebroadcast the BBC World Service in 1998.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In addition to the airport, Auckland International Airport Limited controls a 500,000 square metre property portfolio surrounding the airport including logistics facilities and distribution warehouses.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The New Zealand School of Tourism's main campus and the ExecuJet Auckland FBO for general aviation flights are located on airport grounds.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The Mānawa Bay outlet mall which features over 100 stores is located on the former Aviation Country Club site north of the airport and was developed by the airport corporation.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Two state highways connect to the airport; State Highway 20A and State Highway 20B.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] State Highway 20A leaves the airport to the north along George Bolt Memorial Drive and travels through Māngere as an expressway before joining State Highway 20.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] State Highway 20B leaves the airport to the east and crosses Pukaki Creek before travelling along Puhinui Road to an interchange with State Highway 20 in Wiri.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] A heavy rail connection from the airport to Auckland CBD was initially conceived as an extension of the Onehunga Branch line via Māngere Bridge and the suburb of Māngere.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Another proposal was the construction of a heavy rail line to the east of the airport to connect with the North Island Main Trunk line near Puhinui Station, or the creation of a loop to connect the airport to both the Onehunga Line and the North Island Main Trunk Line.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The preferred option between 2016 and 2024 was an entirely new light rail line running from the airport to central Auckland via a direct alignment through Mangere, Onehunga and Mount Roskill.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] At Mount Roskill, it would have connected to the planned Dominion Road light rail line which would have continued on to Queen Street in Central Auckland before reaching a final terminus in the Wynyard Quarter waterfront development area.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] This project was cancelled by the new National government in January 2024.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] There are several cycle routes connecting the airport to the surrounding suburbs, consisting of both off-road tracks and on-road cycle lanes.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Construction for Stage One started in November 2007.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Stage Two saw the runway being lengthened to 1,650 metres (5,410 ft), which enabled domestic jet flights to use it.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Stage Three (final stage) brought the lengthening of the runway to 2,150 metres (7,050 ft), allowing medium-sized international jet flights to land there, from destinations such as the Pacific Islands or Australia.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Eventually a new domestic terminal would also be built to the north to better utilise the new runway.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The new runway will thus free up the longer southern runway to handle more heavy jet operations.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The ten-year project would cost NZ$120 million, not including substantial extensions planned for the airport arrivals/departure buildings and associated structures.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In early 2014, the airport released their 30-year vision for the future, which envisaged the airport to combine both the international and domestic operations into one combined building based around the existing international terminal.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] This will see new domestic piers built to the south of the existing international precinct within the next 5 years.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The plan also allows for the extension of the current international piers and also the creation of new piers for international operations.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] A new 2,150-metre (7,050 ft) long northern runway will be able to cater for aircraft up to the size of the 777 and 787 jets.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] New public transport links including a new railway station and line may be built in the future.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The plan has been split into four implementation phases.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Phase 1 will see all operations combined into one terminal precinct as well as improved road network surrounding the terminal within the next five years.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Phase 2 sees the new northern runway constructed as well as the extension of the terminal forecourt by 2025.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Phase 3 involves the extension of both international and domestic piers by 2044.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Phase 4 sees the northern runway extended to a length of around 3,000 metres (9,800 ft).
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] In March 2025, the airport began building an alternative runway ahead of planned works on its main runway in 2030.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Auckland connects to 23 domestic and 41 international destinations in North and South America, Asia, Oceania and the Middle East.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Air New Zealand operates the most departures from the airport, followed by Jetstar and Qantas.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] On 17 September 2022, Auckland Airport marked a milestone in ultra-long-haul travel with the launch of services to New York's John F.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Kennedy Airport (about 16 hours eastbound), the world's fifth-longest scheduled route, operated by Air New Zealand and Qantas.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The statistical area of Auckland Airport covers 23.05 km2 (8.90 sq mi), and extends northwest of the actual airport to include Puketutu Island.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] It had an estimated population of 550 as of June 2025, with a population density of 24 people per km2.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Auckland Airport had a population of 528 in the 2023 New Zealand census, a decrease of 102 people (−16.2%) since the 2018 census, and a decrease of 39 people (−6.9%) since the 2013 census.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] There were 252 males and 276 females in 156 dwellings.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The median age was 30.7 years (compared with 38.1 years nationally).
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] People could identify as more than one ethnicity.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] English was spoken by 96.0%, Māori language by 17.6%, Samoan by 6.8%, and other languages by 9.1%.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] No language could be spoken by 2.3% (e.g. too young to talk).
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] New Zealand Sign Language was known by 0.6%.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The percentage of people born overseas was 19.9, compared with 28.8% nationally.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Religious affiliations were 36.9% Christian, 4.5% Hindu, 1.7% Islam, 5.7% Māori religious beliefs, 0.6% Buddhist, 0.6% New Age, 0.6% Jewish, and 1.1% other religions.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] People who answered that they had no religion were 43.2%, and 5.7% of people did not answer the census question.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] Of those at least 15 years old, 57 (14.3%) people had a bachelor's or higher degree, 222 (55.6%) had a post-high school certificate or diploma, and 126 (31.6%) people exclusively held high school qualifications.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The median income was $40,600, compared with $41,500 nationally.
[src:ambury-regional-park/airport-oaks] The employment status of those at least 15 was that 213 (53.4%) people were employed full-time, 36 (9.0%) were part-time, and 24 (6.0%) were unemployed.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Akaroa Marine Reserve and the nearby Pōhatu Marine Reserve are no-take zones.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The harbour as a whole has considerable natural values, and the fauna of the inner and outer harbour differs.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are pressures on the ecology from human activity, such as settlements on the edge of the harbour, and land and water-based industrial activity.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The marine boundary of Akaroa Marine Reserve is almost entirely surrounded by Akaroa Taiāpure, which occupies the rest of the harbour and the ocean coast between the Akaroa and Pōhatu reserves.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure is a local fishing co-management tool for the harbour, which has customarily been of special significance to the hapū as a source of food for spiritual and cultural reasons.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established over 90 percent of the harbour in February 2006.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] It allows Te Rūnanga o Ngāi Tahu (tribal council) and other fisheries stakeholders to have a say in how the harbour is managed.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishing can continue in taiāpure, subject to rules and regulations.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure complements the reserve (the remaining 10% of the harbour), as does Pōhatu Marine Reserve just outside the harbour entrance, in Pōhatu / Flea Bay, plus Lyttelton Harbour's Port Levy Mātaitai Reserve and Rāpaki Mātaitai Reserve.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] A *mātaitai* is a permanent reserve created in areas of traditional importance to Māori for customary food gathering.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The two marine reserves are total no-take areas, whereas the taiāpure and mātaitai are fishing enabling and not about the protection of marine life.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Indeed, the *tangata tiaki* (marine guardian) has the power to override fishing regulations, and moreover, the taking of kelp by one pāua farmer is enshrined in the taiāpure legislation.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Taiāpure Management Committee is a non-elected group largely made up of Ngāi Tahu representatives and a range of fisheries interest groups, including recreational, commercial, marine farmers and marine tourism operators.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] This committee has no control over the number of recreational anglers, hence no control over the total number of fish and shellfish taken.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, people with local knowledge knew that fish stocks were nowhere near as plentiful as they once were.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Māori who had fished the harbour for decades had lost the opportunity of fishing freely along its shoreline.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The *rūnanga* (committee of senior decision-makers of an *iwi* (tribal group) or *hapū* (family, district groups or community)) knew that pollution and over-fishing had diminished the area of available *mahinga kai* (traditional food gathering areas) within the harbour.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Pollution includes sewage, farm and sub-division run-off as well as algal blooms.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Forest and Bird carried out exploratory dives in Akaroa Harbour in 1990.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Harbour Marine Protection Society formally proposed the establishment of a 560-hectare (1,400-acre) marine reserve in 1996.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The proposal was divisive and led to a two-decade battle that pitted a small group of vocal and determined local residents and divers against recreational anglers, *rūnanga*, commercial fishers and one aquaculturalist.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The local residents wanted a no-take area in the eastern waters of the outer harbour to acts as a breeding pool and as place for dolphins to feed.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Recreational anglers argued "that's where we fish in a northeasterly".
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Te Runanga o Ngāi Tahu claimed strong ties to the area, naming it Te Whata o Kōkiro (meaning the food store-house of Kokiro).
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] When the marine reserve idea was first mooted, commercial fishing was a part of Akaroa's economy and commercial fishers strongly opposed it.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] During the long battle, fish stock declined, and so did commercial fishing.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The original proposal called for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers counteracted that proposal by applying for and getting a smaller 215 hectares (530 acres) hectares reserve to be located outside of the harbour, at sheltered bay named Pōhatu / Flea Bay.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] While eco-tourism operators were pleased to have something to show to tourists, local iwi continued to express concerns that marine reserves hindered their traditional rights to harvest from the sea.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Meanwhile, the local residents group continued to advocate for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Fisheries Act 1996 Part 9 Section 174–175 provides for the establishment of taiāpure/fisheries co-management by local people who care about and have strong ties to an area.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In January 2004, the Māori Land Court tribunal made a recommendation to the Minister of Fisheries that a taiāpure be granted over the whole of Akaroa Harbour bar one small area subject to the, at that time, proposed Akaroa Marine Reserve.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Judge Wainwright saw no reason why the two could not live together.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, this recommendation was successfully appealed by the local pāua farmer and kelp harvester, who claimed a taiāpure would compromise his business.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The High Court sent the case back to the tribunal to gather further evidence about whether the whole of Akaroa Harbour does or does not come within the concept of "littoral coastal waters" of "special cultural significance" to the rūnanga.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The pāua farmer eventually reached an understanding with Ngāi Tahu, ending years of argument.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] He has been granted the rights to harvest giant bladder kelp (*Macrocystis pyrifera*), which he uses to feed the pāua at the Akaroa Paua Farm and also to make garden fertiliser and kelp pepper.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In contrast, the East Otago Taiāpure explicitly prohibits the harvesting of kelp.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] That ban does not extend to unattached beach-cast kelp.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are environmental concerns in Akaroa Harbour regarding the ecological disruption caused by kelp harvesting to wild pāua and other *kaimoana* (sea food).
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established in February 2006, but the marine reserve took eight more years.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Conservation Minister Kate Wilkinson declined the application for the reserve in 2010 on the grounds that it would adversely affect recreational fishing.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The decision was challenged in the High Court and was quashed in a 2012 ruling.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In terms of actual numbers, the two separate consultation processes for the application had attracted more support than opposition.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In April 2013 Conservation Minister Nick Smith announced the approval of the reserve but at the reduced size of 465 hectares (1,150 acres).
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Smith believed the battle had gone on for too long.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The size was reduced to take into account the concerns about customary and recreational fishing.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Subsequently, the size was finalised as 512 hectares (1,270 acres).
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Environment Minister Amy Adams expressed an aspiration for the next step to be integrating the local management of taiāpure and reserve so the two mechanisms work together.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] New Zealand fishing rules place reduced bag limits on many fish species and prohibit shellfish gathering in specific areas.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Tangata tiaki (marine guardians) are appointed for Ōnuku Runanga *rōhe moana* (defined customary fishing area) by the Minister of Primary Industries.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The tangata tiaki (also known as kaitiaki) receive training in bylaws, what quantities of various species can be taken, dates or seasons recommended for harvest, size limits and methods of harvest.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers can get a kaitiaki permit from the tangata tiaki granting permission to take over and above the catch limit, and under the legal size.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] This permit, colloquially called a "chit", is given for *tangihanga* (funeral), *hui* (gathering) and other occasions.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In addition to upping catch limits, the kaitiaki has the power to override other fishing regulations.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2018, the Department of Conservation trialled a baited underwater video study, which provided a snapshot of the fish communities both within and outside the Akaroa and Pōhatu marine reserves.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] A total of 28 fish species were identified, demonstrating that the baited underwater video technique is an effective method for examining the size and relative abundance of these species.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The study found notable differences in the relative abundances and sizes of blue cod and blue moki in the marine reserves when compared to three taiāpure control areas.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, since there is no baseline data for Akaroa Marine Reserve, it would be hasty to link these spatial variations to their protection status.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Nonetheless, the results indicated an increase in the abundance and size of blue cod and moki at Pōhatu reserve compared to earlier studies, and that is likely due to the protection from direct fishing pressure.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2021, a three-year initiative called *Iongairo* was launched to supply data that aids in the management of customary fishing zones and enhances understanding of marine reserves in Te Pātaka o Rākaihautū/Banks Peninsula.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] *Iongairo* focused on identifying and evaluating important habitats—including rock, sand, and mud—and key species such as pāua, mussels, and various types of seaweed.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Additionally, it examined the effects of human activities on the environment.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Methods included baited underwater cameras, towed and dropped cameras, along with sediment grabs.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The outcome is an interactive online map showcasing the seafloor.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] The park is owned and managed by Greater Wellington Regional Council, making it one of the largest landowners in New Zealand.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa is a Māori name meaning 'Trailing vines'.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Activities include cycling, hunting, fishing, horse riding, 4WD-vehicle trips and trail biking, including at the Karapoti Gorge.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa Forest has ancient northern rātā which predate human habitation of New Zealand, including one tree which is believed to be 1100 years old.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Some of these trees are wider than Tāne Mahuta.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] One is largest rātā tree in New Zealand, at 39 metres tall.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Greater Wellington Regional Council carried out a 1080 dropping programme in 2013 to reduce pest species.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] A trailbiker was seriously injured in the park in July 2017.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] A dirt-biker was rescued from the forest in February 2021.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Between December 2017 and August 2018, a 1.7 kilometre zig-zag track that is part of the Cannon Point Walkway was closed to the public due to a disagreement between Upper Hutt City Council and a private landowner over land access.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] In early 2021, Forest and Bird campaigned for Upper Hutt City Council to keep a 35-hectare block as a wildlife corridor and reserve, connecting Akatarawa Forest with Wainuiomata.
[src:ambury-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] In July 2021, a further 1080 operation was carried out in 2021 to combat a resurgence in possum numbers.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] Albany ward covers 179.74 km2 (69.40 sq mi) and had an estimated population of 205,600 as of June 2025, with a population density of 1,144 people per km2.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] Albany ward had a population of 190,992 in the 2023 New Zealand census, an increase of 24,138 people (14.5%) since the 2018 census, and an increase of 47,493 people (33.1%) since the 2013 census.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] There were 93,375 males, 97,008 females and 606 people of other genders in 65,652 dwellings.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] The median age was 39.4 years (compared with 38.1 years nationally).
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] The results were 65.1% European (Pākehā); 6.7% Māori; 2.7% Pasifika; 30.6% Asian; 2.8% Middle Eastern, Latin American and African New Zealanders (MELAA); and 2.2% other, which includes people giving their ethnicity as "New Zealander".
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] English was spoken by 92.9%, Māori language by 1.1%, Samoan by 0.3%, and other languages by 31.1%.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] No language could be spoken by 2.1% (e.g. too young to talk).
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] New Zealand Sign Language was known by 0.3%.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] The percentage of people born overseas was 47.0, compared with 28.8% nationally.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] Religious affiliations were 31.8% Christian, 2.0% Hindu, 1.3% Islam, 0.2% Māori religious beliefs, 1.5% Buddhist, 0.3% New Age, 0.2% Jewish, and 1.2% other religions.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] People who answered that they had no religion were 55.4%, and 6.2% of people did not answer the census question.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] Of those at least 15 years old, 53,556 (34.5%) people had a bachelor's or higher degree, 67,665 (43.6%) had a post-high school certificate or diploma, and 34,080 (21.9%) people exclusively held high school qualifications.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] The median income was $47,200, compared with $41,500 nationally.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albany-ward-local-government] The employment status of those at least 15 was that 81,450 (52.4%) people were employed full-time, 21,012 (13.5%) were part-time, and 3,384 (2.2%) were unemployed.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] The **Albert-Eden-Puketāpapa Ward** is an Auckland Council ward which elects two councillors and covers the Albert-Eden and Puketāpapa Local Boards.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] Currently the councillors are Christine Fletcher and Julie Fairey.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] Prior to 2019, this ward was known as the **Albert-Eden-Roskill Ward**.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] Albert-Eden-Puketāpapa ward covers 48.19 km2 (18.61 sq mi) and had an estimated population of 170,300 as of June 2025, with a population density of 3,534 people per km2.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] Albert-Eden-Puketāpapa ward had a population of 158,010 in the 2023 New Zealand census, a decrease of 2,571 people (−1.6%) since the 2018 census, and an increase of 6,513 people (4.3%) since the 2013 census.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] There were 77,853 males, 79,230 females and 927 people of other genders in 53,376 dwellings.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] The median age was 35.7 years (compared with 38.1 years nationally).
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] The results were 48.6% European (Pākehā); 7.9% Māori; 11.1% Pasifika; 39.4% Asian; 3.9% Middle Eastern, Latin American and African New Zealanders (MELAA); and 1.5% other, which includes people giving their ethnicity as "New Zealander".
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] English was spoken by 92.2%, Māori language by 1.8%, Samoan by 2.6%, and other languages by 34.6%.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] No language could be spoken by 2.0% (e.g. too young to talk).
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] New Zealand Sign Language was known by 0.4%.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] The percentage of people born overseas was 45.3, compared with 28.8% nationally.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] Religious affiliations were 29.4% Christian, 8.3% Hindu, 4.7% Islam, 0.3% Māori religious beliefs, 2.3% Buddhist, 0.4% New Age, 0.2% Jewish, and 1.8% other religions.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] People who answered that they had no religion were 47.4%, and 5.4% of people did not answer the census question.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] Of those at least 15 years old, 57,186 (43.1%) people had a bachelor's or higher degree, 47,160 (35.6%) had a post-high school certificate or diploma, and 28,299 (21.3%) people exclusively held high school qualifications.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] The median income was $47,300, compared with $41,500 nationally.
[src:ambury-regional-park/albert-eden-puketāpapa-ward] The employment status of those at least 15 was that 72,195 (54.4%) people were employed full-time, 17,052 (12.9%) were part-time, and 4,089 (3.1%) were unemployed.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The park is a working sheep and dairy farm with a woolshed and milking shed.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] There are also goats, cows, pigs, chickens, turkey, rabbits and peacocks.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Areas of the park are leased to the Mangere Pony Club, and the Ambury Park Centre for Riding Therapy, a charity which opened in 1985, which provides physiological and psychological therapy through horse riding.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The parks hosts the Ambury Farm Day each year.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] It is the largest annual event organised by Auckland Council, and gives families free access to a working farm.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The park covers 85 hectares (210 acres) of low-lying volcanic land on the shores of the upper Manukau Harbour.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] It includes both camping coastline, grazed farming paddocks, wetlands, saltmarshes and small areas of native forest.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Much of Ambury Regional Park formed approximately 50,000 years ago, during an eruption of Māngere Mountain.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] There are several examples of basalt lava flows, originating from the Māngere Mountain about 18,000 years ago.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Most other lava flows around Auckland have been destroyed during urban development.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Large numbers of migratory shorebirds visit Ambury Regional Park and the surrounding areas of the Manukau Harbour, with an estimated number of 28,000 tōrea and 1,200 ngutuparore (wrybills) migrating north from the South Island after breeding over the winter.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] During summer months, an estimated 12,000 kuaka (bar-tailed godwits) and 9,000 huahou (red knots) spend summer months in the vicinity of the park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Kōtuku ngutupapa (royal spoonbill) also migrate to the area.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Birdwatchers have identified a total of 86 birds in the park including little shags, and white-faced herons.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] In 2015, a vegetation survey identified 40 native species in Ambury Regional Park, including the nationally vulnerable species *Geranium retrorsum*, and oioi-coastal needle grass, only rarely seen in saline volcanic soil in the Auckland Region.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] There is an extensive history of Māori settlement in the Māngere Mountain area, and there are 95 archaeological sites around the park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] During the mid-19th century, the area was converted to farmland.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] In 1882, the Ambury English & Co milk company established a creamery on a 260 acres (110 ha) farm on Wallace Road.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] In the late 1960s, the Māngere sewage treatment was established on the shores of the Manukau Harbour.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Over 500 hectares (1,200 acres) of oxidation ponds were decommissioned, 13 kilometres (8.1 mi) of shoreline were restored, beaches were constructed, and 27,000 trees were planted in New Zealand's largest coastal restoration project, which was officially completed in 2005.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] During the 1960s, the Auckland Regional Authority purchased land adjacent to the Māngere sewage treatment plant as a buffer.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] From une 1973, local community groups were able to user the land, and in 1977 an educational farm was established at the site.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Ambury Regional Park was officially opened on 26 September 1987.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] In 1985, a fuel pipeline between Marsden Point and Auckland Airport was laid through the park.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The route is marked by white fenceposts, farm gate tags and triangular marine markers.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] In December 1986, the Ambury Regional Park was the site of a large-scale Mongrel Mob convention, where over 300 members attended, during which gang members helped complete the rock retaining walls along the Manukau waterfront.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] A kidnapping and sexual assault at this event became national news.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The annual Ambury Farm Day began in 1988.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] By the early 2000s, the park had become a popular school excursion, with 3-4 schools booked per week visiting the working farm.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] A new concept plan for the park was developed in 2009, which included linking it up to nearby walk and cycling tracks.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] By that stage, 25,000 people were visiting the park each year outside of the annual farm day.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] By the late 2010s, around 400,000 people had begun visiting the park annually.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] There are a range of facilities, including public toilets and barbecues.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The campground can accommodate up to 60 people.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The park is connected by walkway and cycleway to the Māngere Bridge to Onehunga in the north-east along Kiwi Esplanade, and the Ihumātao to the south.
[src:ambury-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] It is within walking distance to the nearest bus stop, and the nearest train station is Onehunga railway station.
